{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_gemsilica_ver01/data/sn95060748/00517019148/1948070101/0160.xml":{"full_text":"Three Weeks Visit\nIn Calif. Planned\nRev. and Mrs. George Harer\nand family are leaving Monday\nmorning for Los Angeles, Calif.,\nwhere they will attend the annual\nFree Methodist Conference to be\nheld for 3 weeks.\nThey also plan to visit her mo\nther, Mrs. Margaret Lingren, Mr.\nand Mrs. J. R. Lockwood, and her\nsister, Mrs. Oscar Olson all at\nVictorville, Calif. Also her bro\nther, Mr. Lawrence Lingren of\nPasadena, Calif., and other rela\ntives.\n]{W J J\nDeclaration of Independence\nHe\u2019s on his own. It\u2019s a wonderful feeling. He can go places\nnow. And he\u2019ll keep on going places all his life \u2014as long as\nhe keeps his sense of independence.\nThat\u2019s America\u2019s richest resource not forest,' field or\nmine, but the spirit of her people. Ambition, energy, self\nreliance are the reasons why individuals and industries\ngrow gjeat from small beginnings.\nTake the electric industry this company, for example.\nA few practical dreamers strung the first lines.\u2019People of faith\nand vision risked their savings. Other folks pombined skill and\nhard work to produce better and better service at lower and\nlower cost creating more and more jobs and carrying the\nbenefits of electric living to more and more people.\nThat\u2019s the American way of progress. Free enterprise,\nvision and hard work. They are what built America and the\nhighest standard of living in the world.\nNo nation has ever found a satisfactory substitute for that\ncombination. No nation ever will.\nfgh\nANNOUNCEMENT\nDR. F. H. PILCHER OFFERS\nEYE SERVICE\nEVERY THURSDAY\nAt DR. GALISON\u2019S CLINIC\nVALENCIA WAY. BUCKEYE. ARIZONA\nEYES EXAMINED GLASSES FITTED\nLENSES REPLACED\nValencia F.H.A. Approved Lots\nResidential and business lots with guar\nanteed insured titles. Priced from $150.00\nto $500.00. F.H.A. building loans secured,\nplans furnished.\nJOHN PURCHASE\nLicensed Real Estate' Brokei\nVALENCIA PHONE 4231\nHaldiman Brothers\nGuardian Insurance Agency\nFIRE, AUTOMOBILE,CASUALTY,\nJgH FIDELITY AND SURETY BONDS\nRepresenting Old Reliable Companies\nSINCE 1897\nTO OR FROM PHOENIX\nA Friendly Welcome On The Road\nWATSON'S\n615 S. 17th Ave.\nLumber Hardware Houseware\nDR. E. B. PEASE\nDENTIST\nImmediate Service to Out-of-Town Pa\ntients Assured by Your Choice of FOUR\nDENTISTS.\nFOX THEATRE BLDG. Phone 43943\nPhoenix, Arizona\nW. W. G. Meeting\nAt Sisson Home\nA World Wide Guild meeting\nwas held Friday afternoon at the\nE. L. Sisson home.\nRefreshments were served.\nPresent were: Joan Biddulph,\nAnne Sisson, Courtenay Van Den\nburgh, Wilma Rowley, Jo Ann\nAmes, Evelyn Aulwurm and\nteacher, Mrs| E. L. Sisson.\nLittle Johnnie Estrada, son of\nMr. and Mrs. Lewis Estrada was\nrushed to Phoenix St. Monica\u2019s\nHospital last week because of ill\nness, but is home now and doing\nnicely.\nBuckeye Valley News, Thursday, July 1,1948\nthe American way\nEHV WE'VE JUST GOT\nTO TAKE THAT\no A PENN vr N i T o T HIS n ,F i\nYEAR J\\ THPOW ENOUGH I ^6\u201c\nI STRIKES PAST\nX^YOU/ 2^/\nParty For Tommy\nWoods Fifth Birthday\nMrs. J. J. Wood entertained a\ngroup of children at a party at\nher home Tuesday afternoon in\nhonor of her son Tommy\u2019s fifth\nbirthday anniversary.\nGames were played on the\nlawn. Tommy received many nice\ngifts. Refreshments of ice cream\ncake and lemonade were served.\nThose present were Ethel Ann\nand Donald Tyree, Gerald, Wayne\nand Darrel Rowland, Virginia\nEstes, Janie Joslin, Linda Narra\nmore, Carol and Sharol Ingersol,\nSammy Richardson, Ronald An\nderson, Wayne Schweikart, Kath\nleen Karstetter, Sharon and\nSandra Wood.\nMothers present were Mes\ndames Vivian Tyree, Orval In\ngersol, Rowland, Richardson and\nAnderson. Mrs. Wood was assist\ned by her sister Jean Karstetter.\nPhoenix Nurses Enjoy\nEvening Here\nA group of nurses from Good\nSamaritan Hospital in Phoenix\nenjoyed a swimming party and\npicnic Friday at the Buckeye\nswimming pool. Wiey were joined\nat the pool by Nurses June Heiden\nand Wanda Burkhart also of\nGood Samaritan, who were at\nhome here, Miss Heiden on her\nday off and Miss Burkhart on va\ncation.\nIn the evening a softball game\nwas played against a mixed Buck\neye girls team. y\nAfter the game the nurses went\nto the Heiden Ranch where they\nenjoyed watermelon.\nMrs. Hanna, assistant superin\ntendent of Good Samaritan and\nMrs. Goldenberg, director of\nnurses accompanied the nurses.\nShower Honors\nMrs. Robt. Buntz\nMrs. Robert Buntz of Arlington\nwas honored at. a Stork Shower\nrecently at the home of Mrs.\nLouis Wingfield.\nThose present were Mrs. Car\nrol Griffin, Mrs. L. Anderson,\nMrs. A. Anderson, Mrs. Bill Ja\ngow, Mrs. Gene Jagow, Mrs.\nWilbur Anderson, Mrs. Jackie\nGable, Mrs. Carter Gable, Mrs.-\nSam Richardson, Mrs. Tony\nKreager, Mrs. Dick Kreager and\nIrene Harris.\nThe honoree received many\nuseful and beautiful gifts. Mrs.\nWingfield and Mrs. Griffin serv\ned refreshments of fancy sand\nwiches, cake, ice cream and\npunch.\nBIRTHDAY PARTY\nMr. and Mrs. D. Figueroa had\na belated birthday party at their\nhome Sunday night of last week\nin honor of their son Chriss Fig\nueroa\u2019s 23rd birthday anniver\nsary.\nThose present were Mr. and\nMrs. Rangel and family of Dixie,\nMr. and Mrs. Robert Buntz, Mr.\nand Mrs. Tony Kreager, Mrs. Dick\nKreager, Mr. and Mrs. Albino\nFigueroa and family, Mr. and\nMrs. James Ray and family of\nSentinel, Mrs. Carter Gable,\nIrene Harris and daughter Bob\nbie, Frank Yanez of Buckeye,\nTom Willcutt, Martha Borrow,\nN. Martine, Jesus and Irene Pablo\nJessie James and \u201cChoppo\u201d of\nSentinel. They served refresh\nments of enchiladas, hot dogs,\npotato salad, cake and ice tea.\nAfter they finished eating all\nwent over to Bob Watson\u2019s place\nand danced for the rest of the\nevening. Every one reported they\nhad a wonderful time. Some of the\ncakes were baked by the Desert\nRose cook (Taco).\nHomestead Drawings\nHeld Wednesday\nYuma, Ariz., June 29^-Flfty\nfour war veterans from 16 states\ntoday were selected by lot to\nhomestead 4,9 40 acres of prede\nveloped land on the Yuma Mesa\nDivision of the Gila Project sev\neral miles east of Yuma.\nThe farms range in sizes of 40\nto 160 acres ahd are planted to\nalfalfa which will be growing at\nthe time the homesteaders settle\non the land later this summer.\nThe Bureau of Reclamation will\ntake care of the land until the\nsettlers can take over.\nNames of the 54 homesteaders\nand of an equal number of alter\nnates were drawn from a glass\njar during a ceremony in the\nAmerican Legion hall attended by\nprominent representatives of mu\nnicipal, state, and Federal agen\ncies and veterans organizations.\nThe jar contained the capsuled\nnames of 609 applicants approved\nby the examining board. The cap\nsules were taken from the con\ntainer by the commanders of lo\ncal veterans\u2019 organizations, and\nopened by Superintendent Joseph\nP. Collopy of the Gila Project.\nThe first name drawn was that\nof John Gardner of Gainesville,\nTexas, Only tour of the 54 were\nMrs. Flood Returns\nFrom Hazardous Trip\nMrs. M. E. Flood arrived home\n.several days ago from a hazard\nous experience when traveling\nhomeward by -bus through Okla\nhoma. At first they were hit by\nheavy rain and a tornado which\nthreatened to blow them away,\nthen on driving into a portion of\nthe .road already covered with wa\nter, the bus, loaded with over 50\npeople, Mrs. Flood said, was\nstruck by a flash flood of roaring\nwater which filled the bus to the\nwindows.\nThe people became hysterical\nand a panic ensued aboard, so she\nquickly made her decision.\nShe climbed through a window\nand swam to safety. Later she as\nsisted others appearing on the\nscene and those, like herself who\nwere-able to swim out, to help\nthoge who were fighting for\ntheir lives. It was dark and car\nlights from the highway were\nthrown on the scene which helped\nto find them. It was figured nine\npeople drowned.\nThe survivors, she included,\nwere taken to a hospital and\ntreated for bruises and shock.\nWhen released, Mrs. Flood flew\nto where she could catch a bus\nand come home.\nFire Dept. Called\nOut Wednesday\nBuckeye Fire Department was\ncalled out Wednesday afternoon\nto extinguish a blaze which start\ned in the shed at the rear of the\nJewelery Shop.\nThe Jeweler smelled the smoke\nand when he investigated it was\nalready beyond his control. He\ngave the alarm and the Fire Boys\nwere there in short order and\nput out the blaze before too much\ndamage was done.\nWhat Is Business\nOutlook In Next Year\nWhat is the outlook for busi\nnes activity, prices, wages, etc.,\nfor the next year or so?\nThe economists seem to be in\nreasonable agreement. There is\nno foreseeable decline in indus\ntrial production in general. No\none is talking about depressions,\nexecpt as a very long range pos\nsibility. Employment, consequent\nly, will remain high.\nMore wage increases are on the\nway General Motors\u2019 recent\nagreement with the auto workers\nprobably indicates the pattern.\nIt is expected that there will\nbe some rise in commodity prices,\nperhaps averaging three or four\nper cent by end of the year. Some\nprices will naturally go up more\nthan others. The new Ford cars,\nas an example, cost about 9 per\ncent more than the previous\nmodels. Only moderate increases\nin food prices are forecast.\nThe influence of the prepared\nness program, which will cost\nabout $13,000,0.00,0 0 0 during\nthe next' fiscal year, is being\nwatched closely. This, coming on\ntop of the European Aid Program,\nwill place another heavy burden\non basic industries. That drain\nmay be severe in the case of ma\nterials now in short supply. From\nthe. consumer\u2019s point of view, it\nwill be marked by a smaller pro\nduction of automobiles and simi\nlar goods than would be the case\notherwise.\nThere is a possibility that the\ntax cut given income taxpayers\nthis year may not be continued in\nthe next. It all depends on the re\nlationship between Federal in\ncome and outgo. Neither party, in\nan election year, seems willing to\ndo much more than talk about\ngovernment economy.\nS. P. Orders 78 New\nStreamlined Cars\nOrders for 78 new streamlined\ncars, including 30 sleeping cars\nand 48 other miscellaneous pas\nsenger cars of latest design, have\nbeen placed by Southern Pacific\nwith The Budd Company, A. T.\nMercier, president of the rail\nroad, announced yesterday.\nThese orders are in connection\nwith the railroad\u2019s recently an\nnounced plan s for complete\nstreamlining of its \u201cSunset Lim\nited,\u201d operating between Los\nAngeles and New Orleans. The 30\nsleeping cars will have room ac\ncomodations only.\nThe 78 passenger cars, togeth\ner with nine Diesel-electric loco\nmotives, costing a total of ap\nproximately $15,000,000, will\nprovide equipment for five com\nplete \u201cSunset Limited\u201d trains,\nthe number required to maintain\ndaily service on the 1996-mile\nrun between the west coast and\npresent. They are: Francis H.\nMartin, Dan E. Connell and John\nR. Scarbrough, all of Yuma, and\nBaldwin W. Foote, of San Diego,\nCalifornia.\nArizona had 8 successful appli\ncants,\nNew Orleans, It was stated. Oi\nders for the locomotives have al\nready been placed with the Amer\nican Locomotive Company.\nIt is expected that delivery of\nthe \"Sunset Limited\u2019s\u2019\u2019 stream\nlined equipment will begin the\nlatter part of next year, according\nto the announcement.\nPersonal Items\nMrs. Leona Donaldson is visit\ning her brother and wife Mr. and\nMrs. W. F. Pinnick.\nMr. and Mrs. Dewey Stephens\nand family spent Tuesday night\nand Wednesday in Prescott visit\ning his sister and family.\nMr. and Mrs. Delbert Wood and\nfamily spent Sunday with Mr. and\nMrs. A. H. Coy in Tolleson. They\nattended a family reunion.\nRev. and Mrs. George Harer and\nfamily visited Thursday with his\nparents Mr. and Mrs. George\nHarer, Sr., in Phoenix.\nMr. and Mrs. Gail Richardson,\nKenneth and Gaila Darlene from\nAjo spent Saturday with her\nparents Mr. and Mrs. A. C. Wood.\nMrs. Luisa Flores has been ser\niously ill for the past wo weeks,\nbut she is now Improving. She\nstayed with her daughter, Mrs.\nRito Ybarra.\nMrs. Mary Newton of Wood\nlake, Calif., aunt of Mrs. Delbert\nWood visited a few days this\nweek with Mr. and Mrs. Delbert\nWood and family.\nSid Davis of Amarillo, Texas\narrived Sunday at the Fred Faver\nhome. He will preach in the All\nYouth Revival held by the\nSouthern Baptist Church.\nThe Yo.ung People\u2019s class of\nthe Community Church enjoyed a\nskating party Saturday night in\nPhoenix. Their teacher is Mr. T.\nV. Pyle.\nMr. Mark Holden went to\nPhoenix Monday to see his sister.\nMrs. J. H. Green, who was under\nobservation at Good Samaritan\nHospital. It is reported she sub\nmitted to a major operation\nWednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Bill Grissom and\n(daughter Mary Elaine who are\nliving at Davis Dam, are expected\nto spend the Fourth of July holi\ndays with her parents Mr. and\nMrs. A Anderson at Arlington.\nMr. and Mrs. Mike Yanez and\nson Michael are planning a trip\nto the Coast where they will visit\nvarious points. With the excep\ntion of calling on relatives at El\nCentro they Intend to visit only\nspots where it Is \"nice and cool\u201d.\nWANT ADS\nLOST: Ladies wrist watch, dime\nsize, hexagon shape, without\ncrystal. Please return to News.\nMrs. Luther Stowers, It\nFRYERS FOR SALE: Call 4511\nor 2nd house south of high\nschool. It\nLIVESTOCK: Bought and Sold.\nCustom hauling, 2 trucks avail\nable anytime. 1 small, 1 large.\nHerb Harvey, Buckeye, Phone\n4942.\nFOR SALE: 7 week old chickens,\nalso heavy laying and roasting\nhens. Ist house East of High\nSchool. It*\nWANTED: Housework, restau\nrant work or care of children.\nSee Margaret and Juanita\nKeatley at Corner of 3rd and\nJackson. 2t*\nWASHER: 1946 model Sears\nRoebuck (Kenmore) excellent\ncondition, inquire Frl. and Sat.\nM. L. Huff, Valencia the 6th\nstreet east of Buckeye Funeral\nHome and 3rd house north. It*\nMILK GOATS for sale sls to $35.\nSee Walter Terry three-fourth\nmi. N.W. of Hassayampa. It*\nFOR SALE: 100 Pullets, will lay\nin October; fuel oil water\nheater and heater. Mike Yanez,\ncall 2787. It\nNEW, 5 ROOM, 2 bedroom, ce\nment stucco house, hard wood\nfloors and Venetian blinds\nthroughout, duct cooling, all\nnew furniture, including elec,\nrefrigerator, range and wash\ning machine. Immediate posses\nsion. Low dwon payment*and\nvdry good terms. Hunter\u2019s Real\nEstate, Phone 2691, house\nphone 2946, Buckeye Arizona.\nFOR RENT 3-room furnished\napartment for couple, to Sept.\n1, 1948. Phone 4046. It\nFOR SALE: Small 2-room house\nwith kitchenette, large lot,\nshade, near school and store.\nIdeal for children. Will sacri-\nTHEIR PROPHET AND HIS COMMANDMENTS\nfUfKi'l I MATE Wo\nn CHEAT mo*\n17 enslave\nmIK L,E WiW\nZR ST6AL \"8\nJ HI WRECK I\n7, vni I H\nt kill\nLOVE IHYCOMMWAM\u00ae\n<8\nIff iff\nI\nReprinted by permission of The Chicago Tribune\nThe atrength of a civilization ia measured always by the scope and\ntenacity of its obstructions to larceny. Those obstructions range from\nlaws against your neighbor picking your pockets to statutes that forbid\nhis counterfeiting your registered trade-marks and stealing your pat\nented inventions, says American Fair Trade Council.\nIncentive to individual enterprise springs primarily from assurances\nthat the fruits of that enterprise will not be stolen. Men seldom plant\ngardens where thieves abound and police protection is inadequate. Thus\nur Trade-Mark Laws, our Fair-Trade Laws and our Patent Laws have\nbeen the strongest factors in persuading our people to that extraor\ndinary effort to create and produce which marks the difference between\na static and a dynamic economy.\nCollectivism,by whatever name, is but organized larceny, aggrandiz\ning and enriching a cunning few\u2014out of declining productivity of the\nmany. Therefore, Communism hates, and seeks to destroy, our laws\nagainst larceny. Henry Wallace, long before he so openly embraced his\nnatural allies, said of our Patent System that it is wrong and that every\nbody should be permitted, without restraint, to make any and all pat\nented products. Naturally, no ons \u00bbhen would have much inducement\nto invent anything. Industrial momentum in America, and our strength\nfor defense, would bo destroyed*\nStapleys Announce\nNew Adv. Manager\nThe O. S. Stapley Company,\npioneer hardware firm, has an\nnounced the appoinment of Mi;.\nCi\nM. A. McKAY\nWilliam A. McKay as Advertising\nManager. The vacancy was creat\ned by the resignation of Karl I.\nImL\nH. R POOLE\nHoman, Advertising Manager for\nthe past four years, who is leav\ning Arizona to live on the West\nCoast.\nFormerly Assistant Advertising\nManager of the Central Arizona\nLight Power Company, McKay\nhas been a resident of Phoenix\nfor the past four years. An active\nmember of the Phoenix Advertis\ning Club, he recently acted as\nTechnical Director and Business\nManager of the Club\u2019s \u201cArizona\nUnlimited\u201d exhibition in New\nYork City. Since then he has told\nthe story of \u201cArizona Unlimited\u201d\nto numerous service clubs in the\nValley in an effort to maintain\nthe interest of Arizona residents\nin publicizing Arizona. His civic\nactivities include membership in\nthe Phoenx YMCA Publcjty Com\nmittee and he* has served as\nNeighborhood Commissioner with\nthe Boy Scouts of America.\nThe appointment of Mr. Arnold\nE. Poole as Supervisor of Mer\nchandise and Operations was al\nso announced by the O. S. Stapley\nCompany. His activities will in\nclude a plan to co-ordinate the\nmerchandise and operations of\nThe O. S. Stapley Company stores\nwith other units of the organiza\ntion. Before coming to Phoenix\nin 1947, Mr. Poole was associated\nwith Sears Roebuck Company\nin Pennsylvania and New York\nHis last position with this firm\nwas as Manager of the Lock port,\nN. Y. Retail Unit. Subsequently\nhe operated his own organization\nunder the name of Poole\u2019s Alad\ndin Enterprises.\nActive in civic life, Mr. Poole\nserved as President of the Lock\nport Rotary Club, Merchants\nfice for cash. Some terms if de\nsired. Ida Sclievene, Redl Es\ntate Broker, Licensed. 2t*\nWANTED: REAL ESTATE LIST\nINGS. Ida Schevene, Real Es\ntate Broker, Licensed, 4t*\nFOR SALE: '34 Plymouth 4-door\nsedan. $150.00. Runs good. F.\nJ. Lancey, Inquire the News. 1*\nFOR SALE: 220 acres of unde\nveloped land on U.S. 80, about\n4 miles S.W. of Buckeye. Land\nadjacent to this acreage is de\nveloped and proven. Will sell\nor trade for residence property\nin Phoenix. Hal H. Rowland,\nBox 312, Athens, Ohio. 3t\nSTRAYED from our place at\nLiberty 1 pure bred Guernsey\nBull about 2 years old. Has no\nbrand or ring in nose and not\ndehorned. Dark fawn color\nwith few white spots. Anyone\nknowing his whereabouts please\nnotify June Brewster phone\n2067.\nAssociation and Credit Bureau\nand was an Elder in the Presby\nterian Church.\nPLUMBING\nAND\nPlumbing Repairs\nT. K. Buzard\nSon\nPhone Litchfield Park\n552\nH Buckeye Post No.\nKB 1826 meets\n\u25a0fl July Bth 22nd\nn t r\n_ J I Veterans\nVeteraM I\nWiTrf\n\u201cHormones Boon To Mother\nhood.\u201d Read how sex hormone',\ntherapy is improving the chances\nof thousands of women in having\nchildren! Spe how medical science\nhas answered the question\nWhy Can\u2019t T Have Baby?\u201d Read\nit in the American Weekly that\ngreat magazine distributed with\nnext Sunday\u2019s Los Angeles Exam\niner.\nBUCKEYE\nCHURCHES\nFIRST CHUItCH OF CHRIST\n(Christian)\nFirst St., and Clanton Ave.\nR. C. Sell, Minister\nSunday Services\n10 a.m. Bible\u2019 School\nR. O. Burkhart, Su pt\n11 a.m. Worship\nSermon: \"\u2019What Makes A Nation\nGreat\u201d\n8 p.m. Song Service and Preach\ning. Topic: \u201cWhen Are We Free\u201d\nWednesday Service\n8 p.m. Prayer and Bible Study\n\"Some one said, \u2018The devil\nnever takes a vacation\u2019. So we\nChristians must ever be on guard\nand ready. Only by constant at\ntendance upon the means of grace\ncan we stand.\n\u201cYou need God and His Church\nCome out Sunday!\u201d\n\u2014The Minister\nASSEMBLY OF GOD CHURCH\nSunday School 9:45\nMorning Worship 11:00\nYouth Evangelism 6:30\nEvangelistic 7:30\nD. E. Gribling, Pastor\nFIRST BAPTIST CHURCH\nSunday School 10 a.m.\nSunday Morning Service 11 a.m.\nBYF 7 p.m. Studies in John\nSunday evening service 8 p.m.\nPrayer meeting and Bible Study\n8 p.m. Wednesday.\nMens prayer meeting 8 p.m.\nThursday.\nE. Bramblet, acting pastor\nCHURCH OF CHRIST\nSouth Valencia Way\nSunday School 10 a.m.\nMorning Worship 11 a.m.\nSunday night service 8 p.m.\nFIRST SOUTHERN/ BAPTIST\nCHURCH\nThird and Eason Streets\nJames E. Clark, Pastor\nThe church with a conviction,\npreaching the Gospel.\nThe city\u2019s largest church and\nthe church with a friendly wel\ncome, where you will enjoy wor\nshipping the Lord.\nSunday School each Lord\u2019s Dya\nbeginning at 10 a.m.\nMorning worship, 11.00 o\u2019clock\nTraining union, 7:30 p.m.\nEvening worship, 8:30 p.m.\nBrotherhood meets each Mon\nday night, mid-week prayer ser\nvice Wednesday night. Thursday\nnight is Youth night.\nW.M.U. meet Friday afternoon\nat 2:30 p.m.\nVisit with us, worship wlth*us.\nCHURCH Of The NAZARENE\nValencia Way and Eason St.\nL. O. Webber, Pastor\nChurch School 9:45 a.m.\nMorning Worship 11:00 a.m.\nNYP Service 7:00 p.m.\nEvangelistic Service 11:00 p.m.\nPrayer service Wed. 7:30 p.m.\nCottage Prayer Service Thurs\nday 7:30 p.m.\nFREE METHODIST CHURCH\nRoosevelt and First Street\nGeo. W. Harer, Pastor\nSunday Services\nBible School\u201410:00 a. m. Dean\nCouch, Su pt.\nWorship, Preaching\u2014ll a. m.\nJunior Service\u20147:oo p. m.Mrs.\nDean Couch, Junior Supt.\nYeung Pepole s Service\u20147:oo\np. m.\nEvening Worship\u2014B:oo p. m.\nWednesday Prayer Meeting and\nBible Study\u2014B:oo p. m.\nLDS CHURCH NOTICE\nServices of the LDS church are\nheld each Sunday starting at\n10 a.m. in the lOOF hall in\nBuckeye.\nST. HENRY\u2019S CATHOLIC\nCHURCH\nSunday Mass 8:30 a.m.\nS. D. ADVENTIST CHURCH\nL. D. Weber, Pastor\nSaturday\nSabbath School\u201410:00 a. m.\nServices\u2014ll:3o a. m.\nPrayer Meeting Wednesday,\n8:00 p. m.\nAll welcome.\nPENTECOSTAL CHURCH OF\nGOD\nThird and Eason Streets\nFrank Gallagher, Pastor\nSunday School at 10 a. m.\nMorning Worship\u2014ll a. m.\nBAPTIST GHURCH\nPalo Verde, Arizona\nA. L. Lanford, Sunday School\nSuperintendent\nJ. Wood, Asst. Supt.\n10 a.m. Bible Hour\n11 a.n. Morning Worship\nBookkeeping\nNOTARIAL WORK\nPhone 2206\nIDA SCHFVENE\nGolden Palomino\nQuarter Horse\nPAN TANNA\nStanding At\nFarmer\u2019s Market\nJ. C. COKER\nFee $15.00 at Service this Season\nReturn Privilege\nFOR MORE THAN 20 YEARS\nG. B. CORN\nREAL ESTATE\nNOTARY PUBLIC\nFIRE INSURANCE\n\u2014AND\u2014\nU. S. DEPARTMENT OF THE\nINTERIOR, BUREAU OF LAND\nMANAGEMENT, \"Washington, D.\nC. June 10, 1948. Notice is here\nby given that on September 4,\n1942, the State of Arizona filed\nexchange application Phoenix\n080687 under section 8 of the act\nof June 28. 1934 (48 Stat. 1269),\nas amended by the act of June\n26, 1936 (49 Stat. 1976), to select\nthe SE% sec. 34. T. 10 S.. R. 19\nE.; lots 1,2, S^NE(4 E%SE%,\nsec. 3; lots 3. 4, S^NWH, SW\nsec. 4; NW%. N%S% see. 9:\nN%. NW%SW^, S% SW% sec.\n10, T. 11 S\u201e R. 19 E.; sec. 10, T.\n17 N., R. 16 E.; secs. 14, 22 and\n34, T. 18 N., R. 16 E.; N% sec.\n22, T. 13 N., R. 20 E.; lots 3 and\n4. sec. 4, T. 1 N., R. 3 W., G.\nS.R.M., containing 4413.55 acres\nof public land in exchange for\nlots 1,2, 4,5, 6,7, SEVINW^,\nE%SW%, SE%SE%, sec 6. T. 10\nS\u201e R. 27 E.; N%, N%S%, SE%-\nSE% sec. 25, secs. 24, 32 and 36,\nT. 11 S\u201e R. 29 E.; E% sec. 36.\nT. 11 S., R. 28 E.; secs. 1 and 2,\nT. 12 S., R. 29 E., G. S.R.M..\ncontaining 4414.92 acres of\nState-owned land. This notice is\nfor the purpose .of allowing all\npersons claiming the selected\nlands or having bona fide objec\ntions to such application an op\nportunity to file their protests or\nother objections in the U. S. Dis\ntrict Land Office at Phoenix, Ari\nzona, or in the Bureau of Land\nManagement, together with evi\ndence that a copy of such protest\nor objection has been served upon\nthe State within 30 days from the\ndate of the first publication of\nthis notice. Marion Clawson, Di\nrector. First publication June 17,\n1948. 7-8\nNOTICE OF SALE OF\nMOTOR VEHICLE\nNotice is hereby given that the\nundersigned, Travis Curry, will\non the 10th day of July 1948, be\ntween the hours of 10 a.m. and 4\np.m of that date, sell, for storage\nand repairs, the following motor\nvehicle:\nDodge 1 ton truck, year 1928.\nMotor number 1001-270. This\nsale will be made in front of my\nplace of business on Sunland\nBoulevard in the town of Buck\neye, Arizona.\nTravis Curry\n4 weeks July 8\nNOTICE OF SALE IN BULK\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN\nthat pursuant to the BULK\nSALES LAW, Section 58-301, Ari\nzona Code Annotated, 1939; Roy\nJ. Seymour intends, to sell, trans\nfer and assign the business\nknown as MIDWAY SERVICE\nSTATION located on Highway 80\nin the Town of Midway, County\nof Maricopa, State of Arizona, to\ngether with all the equipment,\nstock in trade, and every other\nthing of value, connected there\nwith to EDWIN A. HUNT and\nthat said sale will be completed\non or before the 22nd day of\nJune, 1948. All creditors having\nclaims should present to the said\nbuyer at Midway Service Station\nMidway, Arizona, prior to June\n22, 1948.\n(signed) Roy J. Seymour\nSTATE OF ARIZONA\nSB\nCounty of Maricopa\nOn this, the 12th day of June,\n1948, before me, the undersigned\nNotary Public, personally ap\npeared Roy J. Seymour, known\nto me (or satisfactorily proven)\nto be the person whose name is\nsubscribed to the above instru\nment and acknowledged to me\nthat <he executed the same for the\npurpose therein contained.\nIN WITNESS WHEREOF I\nhereunto set my hand and official\nseal.\n(SEAL) G. M. Fry\nNotary Public\nMy commission expires:\n10-31-51 3 July 1\nU. S. DEPARTMENT OF THE\nINTERIOR, BUREAU OF LAND\nMANAGEMENT, Washington, D.\nC. June 3, 1948. Notice is hereby\ngiven that on April 17, 1943, the\nState of Arizona filed application\nPhoenix 080834 under section 8 of\nthe act of June 28. 1934 (48\nStat. 1269), as amended by the\nact of June 26, 1939 (49 Stat.\n1976), to select the NW%NE%,\nE%W% sec. 19, E%W% sec. 30,\nT. 1 N\u201e R. 6 W.; E% sec. 26,\nsecs. 28 and 30, N%NW% sec.\n34, T. 24 N., R. 5 W.; S^, NW%\nsec. 13, T. 31 N., R. 4 W.; N%-\nN% sec. 22, T. 32 N., R. 5 W.;\nlots 1,5, 6, sec. 4, T. 10 N\u201e R. 7\nW., G. S.R.M., containing\n2799.13 acres, in exchange for\nsec. 16, lots 6,7, W^SEU,\nSW% sec. 3, T. 21 S., R. 21 E.\u2018\nS% sec. 16, T. 19 S., R. 26 E.;\nSE%NW%, NE%SW%, W%-\nW% sec. 36, T. 11 S., R. 9 E.;\nS%N% sec. 3, T. 1 S., R. 5 W.;\nlots 1,2, 3, sec. 2, T. 10 S., R. 13\nW., G. S.R.M., containing\n1792.41 acres, together with un\nsurveyed land estimated by pro\ntraction to contain 1000 acres.\nThis notice is for the purpose of\nallowing all persons claiming the\nselected land or having bona fide\nobjections to such application an\nopportunity to file their protests\nor other objections in the U. S.\nDistrict Land Office at Phoenix,\nArizona, or in the Bureau of Land\nManagement, together with evi\ndence that a copy of such protest\nor objection has been served upon\nthe State within 30 days from the\ndate of the first publication of\nthis notice. Marion Clawson, Di\nrector. First publication June 10,\nIMB. Last pub Julyl, 1948.","height":"26358","width":"20160"}}
